                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.00/12418: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in China (<persName type="from"
                            >Johnson</persName>) to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Peiping</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1933-08-26T11:00:00+08:00"
                            >August 26, 1933—11 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received August 26—4:10 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>708. Following from Foochow: <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“August 25, 7 p.m. An American missionary at Yenping telegraphed this
                            afternoon that Wangtai, about 45 li from Yenping, had been taken by
                            Communist forces and that the situation at Yenping was critical. He
                            requested that the Consulate telegraph to the officials at Yenping to
                            release a launch for the use of evacuating Americans. The Consulate
                            telegraphed immediately an appropriate request to General Liu Ho-ting,
                            commanding the troops at Yenping, and then succeeded in having similar
                            telegrams despatched from the Provincial Government, Peace Preservation
                            Corps and the local representative of General Liu.</p>
                        <p>A later telegram from the missionary stated that the local officials
                            requested that he ‘Notify Consul they take responsibility for our
                            safety’.</p>
                        <p>In its reply, the Consulate urged that he take no unnecessary risks.</p>
                        <p>There are four Americans in Yenping, two in Kienningfu and one in
                            Kienyang. All have been notified by telegraph.”</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Johnson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
